        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(whatsapp): remove dead Math.max in watchdog app-silence formula",
        "body": "## Problem\n\n`WhatsAppConnectionController` computes the app-silence timeout at construction:\n\n```typescript\n// connection-controller.ts:366 (before fix)\nthis.appSilenceTimeoutMs = Math.max(params.messageTimeoutMs, params.messageTimeoutMs * 4);\n```\n\n`messageTimeoutMs * 4` is always `≥ messageTimeoutMs`, so `Math.max` unconditionally returns `messageTimeoutMs * 4`. The guard is dead code — a reader expecting `Math.max` to do something meaningful will be confused, and a future refactor that replaces the second argument (intending to raise the floor) will silently break the intended behaviour.\n\nDefault values: `messageTimeoutMs = 30 min` → `appSilenceTimeoutMs = 120 min`. Runtime effect is unchanged; this is a correctness/clarity fix.\n\n## Fix\n\nRemove the dead `Math.max` wrapper:\n\n```typescript\n// connection-controller.ts:366 (after fix)\nthis.appSilenceTimeoutMs = params.messageTimeoutMs * 4;\n```\n\n## Test\n\nAdded a test in `connection-controller.test.ts`:\n*\"uses messageTimeoutMs × 4 as the app-silence window for fresh connections with no inbound\"*\n\nAdvances fake-timer time to just before the 4× window → no timeout; then past it → timeout fires. This pins the multiplier as a regression guard against future edits that alter the constant.\n\nAll 14 `connection-controller` tests pass.\n\nSpotted while auditing the watchdog reconnect path on a production deployment.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed:** `appSilenceTimeoutMs` was computed as `Math.max(messageTimeoutMs, messageTimeoutMs * 4)`. Since `messageTimeoutMs * 4 >= messageTimeoutMs` for all positive timeouts, the `Math.max` is dead code that always returns `messageTimeoutMs * 4`. This change removes it. The fix must be behavior-preserving — the watchdog's app-silence window must not change.\n- **Real environment tested:** OpenClaw checkout on macOS (Darwin arm64, Node v22). Constructed the actual patched `WhatsAppConnectionController` from this branch via `node --import tsx` and read back the app-silence window it computes for representative timeout values.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:** instantiated the real controller for `messageTimeoutMs` ∈ {5000, 30000, 120000} and compared the live `appSilenceTimeoutMs` field against both the old `Math.max(...)` formula and the new `* 4` formula:\n  `node --import tsx proof-watchdog.mts`\n- **Evidence after fix:** live stdout from the patched controller:\n\n```console\n$ node --import tsx proof-watchdog.mts\nmessageTimeoutMs=5000 -> controller.appSilenceTimeoutMs=20000 (old Math.max=20000, new=20000) match=true\nmessageTimeoutMs=30000 -> controller.appSilenceTimeoutMs=120000 (old Math.max=120000, new=120000) match=true\nmessageTimeoutMs=120000 -> controller.appSilenceTimeoutMs=480000 (old Math.max=480000, new=480000) match=true\nRESULT: live controller computes the identical app-silence window pre/post change — behavior-preserving dead-code removal\n```\n\n- **Observed result after fix:** the live controller computes exactly `messageTimeoutMs * 4` for every case, identical to the pre-fix `Math.max` output (20s, 120s, 480s respectively). Confirms the watchdog's behavior is unchanged and the removed branch was dead code.\n- **What was not tested:** an end-to-end watchdog force-close against a live socket was not run; this proof targets the computed timeout value the watchdog uses, which is the only thing the change touches.\n",
        "branch": "fix/whatsapp-watchdog-silence-formula",
